Europe
------
[1] Germany (Berlin/Bavaria)
Date: Fri 28 Jun 2013
Source: Berliner Morgenpost [In German, mach. trans., summ., edited]
http://www.morgenpost.de/web-wissen/gesundheit/article117531815/Schwere-Masern-Epidemie-in-Berlin-und-Bayern.html


Germany has reported more than 300 cases of measles since the beginning of the year [2013]. The worst affected have been Berlin and Bavaria. More than 82 percent of the cases of infection were registered in these federal states. In Berlin, 323 cases have already been diagnosed. In 2001 there were 51 cases, then the numbers decreased 2-fold and then rose to 160 in 2011. Now, a new high has been reached already by June [2013].

"This year especially, many adults have also been infected with the measles virus," says Regina Kneiding of the press office of the Senate Health Administration. The Senate has therefore expanded the recommendation for vaccination. All Berliners should check their vaccination status and be immunized in the absence of protection, regardless of age. The usual recommendation from the Standing Committee on Vaccination (STIKO) of the Robert Koch Institute recommends adult vaccination, but so far only for those born after 1970, the date when comprehensive measles vaccination was introduced. But that may leave some adults over the age of 43 unprotected.

This was revealed by a recent case at the Charite [a hospital in Berlin]. A 10-month-old girl had been treated by a doctor. Only a few days later did it became clear that the doctor was not suffering from a cold as supposed, but in fact had contracted measles virus infection. That the doctor had transmitted measles, however, could not be confirmed, since the measles epidemic had broken out already by this time in Berlin; 9 days had elapsed between the diagnoses of measles in doctor and child. It is appropriate now to introduce universal vaccination.

Vaccination complications are extremely rare. "To be involved in a traffic accident or be struck by lightning are more likely events. However, sometimes the elderly or the immune-compromised are affected by some fatal complications such as pneumonia. This shows well that measles is a threat not just for children. Very rarely even younger healthy people can suffer severely from measles virus infection. One in 1000 people suffers a brain inflammation and one in 10 000 suffer subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (SSPE) -- a particularly dreaded complication. SSPE has a long incubation period. With a delay of some years there occurs a progressive loss of brain nerve cells. It will initially cause mental and intellectual changes that follow later with seizures and loss of essential nerve function and even death. Just recently, a 14-year-old from North Rhine-Westphalia [state] developed this condition and died. He had been infected at the age of 5 months in the waiting room of his paediatrician. In this instance the child contracted measles before the time of initial vaccination at one year of age. Before that time, newborn babies are mainly rely on one thing for their protection: the vaccination of their parents and adult contacts. Anyone who wants to protect themselves and others should quickly check their measles vaccination status. Because measles is not just a childhood disease -- but is also a serious health risk.

[Byline: Shari Langemak]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[One consequence of universal vaccination is that subacute sclerosing panencephalitis (SSPE) is rarely mentioned nowadays. SSPE is a progressive neurological disorder of children and young adults that affects the central nervous system (CNS). It is a slow, but persistent, viral infection caused by defective measles virus. The incidence of SSPE declined by at least 90 percent in countries that have practiced widespread immunization with measles vaccine. There is a higher incidence among males than females (male/female: 3/1). Most children with SSPE have a history of measles infection at an early age, usually younger than 2 years, followed by a latent period of 6 to 8 years before neurological symptoms begin. The initial symptoms of SSPE are subtle and include mild mental deterioration (such as memory loss) and changes in behavior (such as irritability) followed by disturbances in motor function, including uncontrollable involuntary jerking movements of the head, trunk or limbs called myoclonic jerks. Seizures may also occur. Death is usually the result of fever, heart failure, or the brain's inability to continue controlling the autonomic nervous system.

A map of Germany showing the locations of Berlin and Bavaria (Bayern) states can be accessed at http://www.planetware.com/map/germany-germany-the-lander-map-d-germany.htm. - Mod.CP

A ProMED-mail HealthMap is available at http://healthmap.org/r/2HYi.]

