[2] UK (airline passenger)
Date: Fri 28 Jun 2013
Source: Health Protection Report Volume 7 No 26 [edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/archives/2013/news2613.htm#msls


Contact tracing following a case of measles in an airline passenger
-------------------------------------------------------------------
Measles incidence in the UK continued at elevated levels during the early months of 2013 -- manifested in local outbreaks in Wales and north-east England, and in higher background levels in England and Scotland. In response, Public Health England's ongoing national catch-up programme, launched in April [2013], aims to prevent measles outbreaks by vaccinating as many unvaccinated and partially vaccinated 10- to 16-year-olds as possible in time for the next school year.

With background incidence being elevated, a putative travel-related risk associated with individual cases may arise, requiring a response from front-line public health professionals. Such a situation arose in Scotland earlier this month when 2 unconnected laboratory confirmed cases of measles were reported to Health Protection Scotland (HPS), both of which had extensive travel during their infectious period. Travel included train (one journey) and flights (7 journeys).

A risk assessment for fellow passengers was undertaken, taking account of European guidance [ECDC guidance: risk assessment guidance for disease transmitted on aircraft, available at http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/1012_GUI_RAGIDA_2.pdf] and following discussion with colleagues at PHE [Public Health England] Centre for Infectious Disease Surveillance and Control. Balancing risk, exposure date, notification date and time scale for administering prophylaxis, HPS undertook contact tracing of passengers on one flight. Using information provided by the airline, around 75 percent of passengers were able to be contacted. The exposure risk was assessed to be low. Passengers were asked about risk factors for complications of measles such as immunosuppression and pregnancy; and their age, history of previous measles infection and vaccination status were discussed. No passengers were identified as requiring prophylaxis and reassurance was provided. Contract tracing for this one flight took about 4 working days of time; it was predominantly conducted over a weekend by the HPS on-call team.

Measles is highly infectious. It is spread through inhalation of droplets generated from an infectious person. A case of measles is infectious from around 4 days before onset of rash to around 4 days after onset of rash. The prodromal period (around 4 days before rash) is usually characterised by symptoms including fever, conjunctivitis, coryza, cough and small spots with white tops in the mouth (Koplik spots). Anyone experiencing these symptoms following known exposure to measles infection should telephone their GP detailing the possible exposure link and avoid public contact. Patients are advised not to travel whilst experiencing these symptoms or for the 1st 4 days of rash. Protection against measles is provided by 2 doses of MMR [measles, mumps and rubella] vaccine. Previous measles infection confers immunity and it is likely that most people born before 1970 had measles infection as a child.

--
