[3] UK (Wales)
Date: Thu 27 Jun 2013
Source: South Wales Evening Post [summ., edited]
http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Measles-outbreak-finally-contained-say-health/story-19405198-detail/story.html#axzz2XWLAprF3


A key milestone has been reached in Swansea to create a "herd immunity" against MMR [measles, mumps and rubella]. Herd immunity effectively stops the MMR viruses in their tracks, but requires a certain proportion of the population to be fully vaccinated. Early indications show that for the 1st time more than 95 per cent of young people in the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board (ABMU) area have had at least one dose of the MMR vaccine. However, herd immunity is only achieved with 2 doses. Health chiefs stressed there is still more to do, with the number of youngsters dosed twice just under 90 per cent.

ABMU Director of Public Health, Sara Hayes, said it was delighted with the progress thus far. Measles is no longer circulating widely, and reported cases have dropped considerably. "The vital next step is to ensure the final few per cent of children and teenagers who still need a 2nd MMR to achieve full protection receive it as soon as possible," she said. "Once we hit 95 per cent of fully vaccinated young people it means that vulnerable members of our community, who can't have MMR because they are too young, or are immune-compromised for example, will be protected from the risk of outbreaks." She added that: "At least 4 weeks needs to pass between the 1st MMR jab and the 2nd to ensure they work properly. "That means that everyone who had their 1st MMR jab at any of our hospital drop-in clinics, or school MMR clinics, can now have their 2nd dose. They should contact their GP to arrange it."

--
