[5] Democratic Republic of Congo (Orientale)
Date: Fri 21 Jun 2013
Source: Radio Okapi (Kinshasa) [In French, trans., edited]
http://healthmap.org/ln.php?1793833&trto=en&trfr=fr&u3409


A total of 356 measles cases with 4 deaths have been recorded since he beginning of January [2013] in the Isiro Health Area of Orientale province of the DRC [Democratic Republic of Congo]. The senior doctor of the Health Zone, Benjamin Anduguwe, stated on Fri 21 Jun 2013 that children in the age range from 0 to 5 years old were most affected by this disease. "At the present time, we have 4 times the number of cases observed in previous years, and a 3-fold increase since the beginning of the year. This is why we have designated this a measles outbreak. We have 10 health areas that are affected, including 7 in urban areas and 3 in rural areas," stated the Chief Medical Officer of Health for the Isiro area.

Dr. Benjamin Anduguwe regretted that most parents in this region preferred to treat their children at home rather than bringing them to health facilities where treatment is free. "There are parents who prefer to treat their children with traditional medicines." The senior doctor of the Isiro Health Zone stated that through the Expanded Program for Immunization (Pev), Isiro had received 2 consignments of aid sufficient to provide free treatment for all children of the district.

In April [2013], Dr. Granga Davuya, the Director of Immunization for UNICEF in the DRC, stated that as of that week, 607 000 children aged 0 to 7 years in the DRC had still not been vaccinated. According to him, the current epidemic of measles reflects the incompleteness of the vaccination programme in the DRC. To ensure that all children are protected, the coverage rate for the population must be greater than 95 percent, and this level of protection had not yet been reached in the DRC. He added, however, that by 2010 the vaccination camping had reduced the mortality rate among children under 5 years, from 213 in 2001 to 158 deaths per 1000 live births.

